pr_review_body:
@steve-ransome Thanks for this submission.

Here is my review of your core algorithm, esp. the normalization and fitting. I have not yet run any examples or looked at the error stacking, plotting functions, or tests.

The main issue I see is potentially more careful handling of the fits in the special case where no windspeed info is provided. I think this should be investigated a bit further and would be happy to discuss.

I'm not convinced this is the way forward. `_payload` in `nailgun/entity_mixins.py` is responsible for translating `OneToManyField` field to `{name}_ids` that is list of ids from entities: https://github.com/SatelliteQE/nailgun/blob/master/nailgun/entity_mixins.py#L182

I think change like that should be applied on framework level, not on each entity level. There are probably many more entities currently broken.

@lhellebr @mshriver @JacobCallahan

Thanks again for taking time to contribute to LightGBM!

I left some small suggestions. Please also fix the linting errors listed in https://travis-ci.org/github/microsoft/LightGBM/jobs/746519935. You can reproduce these errors locally by running `Rscript .ci/lint_r_code.R $(pwd)`.

@zenggyu one other question...are you interested in completely finishing #3390 ? I originally set it up file-by-file like that for Hacktoberfest, but now that Hacktoberfest is over I'd like to finish it. If you have the time and interest, I'd be grateful if you'd handle the rest of the files there in one or two additional pull requests after this one (doesn't have to be one-fiile-per-PR).

@vfdev-5 Thanks for the PR.

I added one suggestion to improve BC during the deprecation period and marked all the places where this could happen. Nevertheless, if our policy is typically to only throw warnings feel free to ignore.

Also I noticed that in some methods you throw warnings while in others you directly replace the names. I assume that this is because the first are considered public API while the latter not. If that's true, then all good.

Awesome work @JessicaBarh Thanks a lot for it.

Regarding the tests, we can directly use the nullTranslator - as we are not testing the translator. I made suggestions in that sense.

@goanpeca I would appreciate a review from you on this one.

Thanks for the PR @aabkn , the changes make sense (although I'm not qualified enough to do a full review). I left a few comments.

I'm curious if https://github.com/scrapinghub/number-parser integration might be useful. Also from the changes it looks like you're parsing free-form text with numbers spelled out as words, is this correct? I'm curious what is the usecase - it might help motivate the number-parser integration better.

@noviluni do you think it makes sense to check performance impact here?

@jvdvegt
Thank you for your pull request.
Could you fix the failed test cases?

@pacrob just curious how you got here to make this change.

I did find [this related conversation](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/19977#issuecomment-618279849) that highlights this as wrong in the spec and was confirmed that the number geth was using, which is the same we have here, is the correct one. I guess the spec you linked never got updated.

Based on that discussion and the fact that [geth still uses the same number we currently use](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/d8ff53dfb8a516f47db37dbc7fd7ad18a1e8a125/accounts/keystore/testdata/v3_test_vector.json#L13) I'm good with actually leaving this as it is and closing this PR.

@GhBlg many thanks for this contribution. We always dream about having all the SOTA models in braindecode! :smile: 

For the implementation, I would reorganize the code a little bit and use classes to make the implementation shorter and clearer. By using two classes (`_InceptionBlock` and `_TCBlock`) we can have less redundant code. It would also correspond better to the structure introduced in the paper. Now it can be a little bit tricky to spot the difference between different blocks.

Let me know, what you think about my propositions and if you have any questions! I am happy to help! :smile:

LGTM

NIT, setting the  `ONLY_DOCS` env variable can be also removed
```
            script {
              dir("${BASE_DIR}"){
                // Skip all the stages except docs for PR's with asciidoc and md changes only
                env.ONLY_DOCS = isGitRegionMatch(patterns: [ '.*\\.(asciidoc|md)' ], shouldMatchAll: true)
              }
            }
```
